{"id":18209,"date":"2025-03-19T09:50:59","date_gmt":"2025-03-19T07:50:59","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/?p=18209"},"modified":"2025-03-19T09:54:40","modified_gmt":"2025-03-19T07:54:40","slug":"sa-mp-calls-for-implementation-of-nama-language-agreement-18-march-2025","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/sa-mp-calls-for-implementation-of-nama-language-agreement-18-march-2025\/","title":{"rendered":"SA MP Calls for Implementation of Nama Language Agreement.18 March 2025"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><img decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-medium wp-image-18210 alignleft\" src=\"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/03\/DEFAULT-6-copy-300x113.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"113\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/03\/DEFAULT-6-copy-300x113.jpg 300w, https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/03\/DEFAULT-6-copy-1024x384.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/03\/DEFAULT-6-copy-768x288.jpg 768w, https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/03\/DEFAULT-6-copy-1536x576.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/www.parliament.na\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/03\/DEFAULT-6-copy.jpg 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Story By: Sakeus Iikela<\/p>\n<p>A South African Member of Parliament has called for urgent action to implement a bilateral agreement on preserving the Nama language between Namibia and South Africa.Speaking in Windhoek on Monday, Hon. Newrene Klaaste, Speaker of the Northern Cape Provincial Legislature, warned that without concrete efforts between the two countries, the language \u2013 a vital part of the region\u2019s cultural heritage \u2013 could disappear.<\/p>\n<p>\u201cOur bilateral agreements with Namibia include education and the preservation of the Nama language. It is crucial that we assess the progress of this agreement. The fear we have is that if we do not actively work to preserve the Damara-Nama language, it will eventually disappear,\u201d she said.<\/p>\n<p>Klaaste made these remarks as part of a high-level South African delegation currently in Namibia for a benchmark study visit to the National Council.The delegation consists of 19 Members of the Legislature, the Secretary to the Legislature, and 20 officials.The purpose of the delegation visit is to conduct a benchmarking activity that affords them the opportunity to learn best practices on issues of oversight; public participation; law-making process; Members&#8217; statements; and resolution tracking, all aimed towards improving their systems and processes in their legislature.The delegation would further strengthen the bonds of friendship, cooperation, and mutual development between our institutions and our nations.<\/p>\n<p>Hon. Klaaste emphasised that the preservation of the Nama language is not just about cultural heritage but about ensuring future generations inherit their rightful linguistic and historical identity.<\/p>\n<p>\u201cThis is not just about culture; it is about ensuring that future generations inherit their rightful linguistic and historical identity,\u201d she said.She further stressed that the agreement should not remain a document with no tangible outcomes but should be actively implemented by both governments.The Speaker also highlighted the historical injustices faced by Nama-speaking communities in South Africa, many of whom were forcibly displaced during apartheid. She reiterated that preserving the is important to restore and maintain the heritage of these affected communities.<\/p>\n<p>Klaaste also proposed the establishment of an exchange program between Namibia and South Africa to further facilitate the sharing of knowledge and strategies between the two parliaments.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Story By: Sakeus Iikela A South African Member of Parliament has called for urgent action to implement a bilateral agreement on preserving the Nama lang